description: Have I had bad experiences with employers? Hell yeah. I‚Äôve had 3 professional jobs from 2001-2021 (one before law school & two as an attorney) & all 3 had massive toxic traits. But I don‚Äôt base this video on that experience. I base it on 14 years of experience as an employment attorney where I represented employees & studied countless cases. I‚Äôve lost count of how many case holdings I‚Äôve read. These records are all public & anyone can access them. You can google it. In addition to public records, I also saw all the confidential agreements & arbitrations of the cases I worked on which are not public & I cannot discuss. Many people think I was only speaking from personal experience when in fact, this is the nature of most workplaces in America. Are there exceptions? Of course there are. Regardless of whether you agree or disagree with my sentiments, I hope you take away the lesson that we should all be building an FU Fund. I first heard this term from JL Collins, the author of a Simple Path to Wealth. Why? Because financial independence is something we should all strive for to help build security & stability in good times & especially in bad times. If the last 2 years hasn‚Äôt taught us that I don‚Äôt know what will. I wouldn‚Äôt bank on an employer‚Äôs good graces as my safety net. That doesn‚Äôt mean you can‚Äôt be friendly at work. Of course you can & you should! But not every colleague deserves your trust & the details about your private life. Use your judgement & be really picky about who you confide in. DO NOT ever think that HR is your friend. They‚Äôre there to represent the company, PERIOD. Many HR managers agreed in the comments of this video so keep that in mind. FU Fund means saying FU to anything or anyone that steals your peace & all it takes is one new manager or coworker to ruin a perfectly fine work environment. Don‚Äôt ever get so comfortable you forget to CYA because I GUARANTEE you your boss & your company is doing just that.

description: There was a TikTok that went viral about a guy bragging that he works 105 hours a week on an oil rig and that anyone who works less than that better ‚Äúcheck themselves.‚Äù Sir, you are the one that has been checked by capitalism. CheckMate.‚Å† ‚Å† People in the United States work more hours and take the least amount of vacation than any other country in the world. Work has become our personality trait. It‚Äôs why we ask people ‚Äúwhat do you do?‚Äù as one of the first questions when we meet them. In other countries, that‚Äôs actually a very rude question.‚Å† ‚Å† In a way, we‚Äôve all been brainwashed to believe this. That working is honorable. That working many, many hours is the right thing, even if you‚Äôre not getting paid for it. That excessive labor is sanctioned by religion even.‚Å† ‚Å† This is unique to our country. And although it has led to so much innovation and financial success, it is not without its cost. The wealth gap is wider than ever. We are in more debt than ever. We can‚Äôt even afford to do the things that our parents could afford to do, like buy a home. Because corporations are gobbling up real estate and jacking up the price.‚Å† ‚Å† All of this is to say: If you‚Äôre working 70+ hours a week, you are probably being exploited (assuming you‚Äôre not being paid multiple six-figures). Many people who leave these types of positions are often replaced by two or three workers because they knew how much work you were doing and they took advantage of you for as long as you let them.‚Å† ‚Å† I hope that you take some time to assess your situation and realize that your health is the priority and you should be working on an exit strategy. Working that many hours for a prolonged period of time is physically and mentally damaging. If you‚Äôre in a position to make a change, I hope that you can. Not everyone is able to, and for that, we have to keep demanding better labor practices from these corporations.‚Å† ‚Å† It‚Äôs time to create an exit strategy!

description: Have you heard of the 4% rule? I‚Äôll cover this during class.  It allows you to withdraw from your portfolio (sell some of your stocks) while allowing the rest of your portfolio to continue growing and compounding. This way you never run out of money. This concept LITERALLY changed my life. I had no idea that this was possible and that it would pave the way for my early retirement goals. Even if you don‚Äôt want to retire early, you need to know how this works so you understand how much you need to have invested by the time you do decide to stop working. And remember that the 4% rule is a guideline and that we need to remain flexible.  Some years you may have to withdraw 2% or 3% but some other years you may get to withdraw 5% or 6% depending on how the market‚Äôs doing.

description: Reposting this since it‚Äôs been a year since I moved to Portugal! $17k for 2 years of health insurance is INSANE and I knew that. You can‚Äôt deduct it as a business expense since it‚Äôs an employer-sponsored plan even though you‚Äôre paying in full. Just get your own policy directly from an insurance company or through the marketplace. I definitely could‚Äôve gone with a cheaper insurance plan. An HMO would‚Äôve cost half. But if I need a specialist I don‚Äôt want to be forced to go to an in-network doctor instead of the one I prefer. I don‚Äôt want to ask for a referral every time. And last but definitely NOT LEAST, I can easily afford this cost. Most people cannot. And just because I can afford it doesn‚Äôt make it any less absurd.
